# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cluster-autoscaling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] In computing, **elasticity** is defined as "the degree to which a system is able to adapt to workload changes by provisioning and de-provisioning resources in an autonomic manner, such that at each point in time the available resources match the current demand as closely as possible".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity is a defining characteristic that differentiates cloud computing from previously proposed distributed computing paradigms, such as grid computing.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] The dynamic adaptation of capacity, e.g., by altering the use of computing resources, to meet a varying workload is called "elastic computing".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] In the world of distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors; some consider the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity aims to match the amount of resources allocated to a service with the amount of resources it actually requires, avoiding over- or under-provisioning.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] **Over-provisioning**, i.e., allocating more resources than required, should be avoided as it may incur extra costs (monetary, energy, operational, etc.) for unused or underutilized resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] For example, if a website is over-provisioned with two cloud computing resources to handle current demand that only requires one resource, the costs of maintaining the second resource would effectively be wasted.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity can be illustrated through an example of a service provider who wants to run a website on the cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] At moment $t_{0}$ , the website is unpopular and a single machine is sufficient to serve all users.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] At moment $t_{1}$ , the website suddenly becomes popular, and a single machine is no longer sufficient to serve all users.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Based on the number of web users simultaneously accessing the website and the resource requirements of the web server, ten machines are needed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and provision nine additional machines from the cloud to serve all users responsively.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] At time $t_{2}$ , the website becomes unpopular again.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] The ten machines currently allocated to the website are mostly idle and a single machine would be sufficient to serve the few users who are accessing the website.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and deprovision nine machines, releasing them to the cloud.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user; however, it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] The VM startup time is dependent on factors such as image size, VM type, data center location, number of VMs, etc.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] This implies that any control mechanism designed for elastic applications must consider the time needed for the resource provisioning actions to take effect.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elastic applications can allocate and deallocate resources on demand for specific application components.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] This makes cloud resources volatile, and traditional monitoring tools which associate monitoring data with a particular resource, such as Ganglia or Nagios, are no longer suitable for monitoring the *behavior* of elastic applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] For example, during its lifetime, a data storage tier of an elastic application might add and remove data storage VMs due to cost and performance requirements, varying the number of used VMs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Thus, additional information is needed in monitoring elastic applications, such as associating the logical application structure over the underlying virtual infrastructure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] When deploying applications in cloud infrastructures (IaaS/PaaS), stakeholder requirements need to be considered in order to ensure that elastic behavior meets stakeholder needs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Traditionally, the optimal trade-off between cost and quality or performance is considered; however, for real world cloud users, requirements regarding elastic behavior are more complex and target multiple dimensions of elasticity (e.g., SYBL).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Cloud applications vary in type and complexity, with multiple levels of artifacts deployed in layers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Controlling such structures must take into consideration a variety of issues.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elastic strategies on in cloud computing can take advantage of control-theoretic methods (e.g., predictive control has been experimented in cloud computing scenarios by showing considerable advantages with respect to reactive methods).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] One approach to multi-level elastic clouc control is rSYBL.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Automatically provision and consolidate the Nodes in your cluster to adapt to demand and optimize cost.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] In order to run workloads in your cluster, you need Nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Nodes in your cluster can be *autoscaled* - dynamically *provisioned*, or *consolidated* to provide needed capacity while optimizing cost.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscaling is performed by Node *autoscalers*.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] If there are Pods in a cluster that can't be scheduled on existing Nodes, new Nodes can be automatically added to the cluster—*provisioned*—to accommodate the Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] This is especially useful if the number of Pods changes over time, for example as a result of combining horizontal workload with Node autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscalers provision the Nodes by creating and deleting cloud provider resources backing them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Most commonly, the resources backing the Nodes are Virtual Machines.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The main goal of provisioning is to make all Pods schedulable.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] This goal is not always attainable because of various limitations, including reaching configured provisioning limits, provisioning configuration not being compatible with a particular set of pods, or the lack of cloud provider capacity.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] While provisioning, Node autoscalers often try to achieve additional goals (for example minimizing the cost of the provisioned Nodes or balancing the number of Nodes between failure domains).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] There are two main inputs to a Node autoscaler when determining Nodes to provision—Pod scheduling constraints, and Node constraints imposed by autoscaler configuration.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscaler configuration may also include other Node provisioning triggers (for example the number of Nodes falling below a configured minimum limit).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Pods can express scheduling constraints to impose limitations on the kind of Nodes they can be scheduled on.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Node autoscalers take these constraints into account to ensure that the pending Pods can be scheduled on the provisioned Nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The most common kind of scheduling constraints are the resource requests specified by Pod containers.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscalers will make sure that the provisioned Nodes have enough resources to satisfy the requests.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] However, they don't directly take into account the real resource usage of the Pods after they start running.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] In order to autoscale Nodes based on actual workload resource usage, you can combine horizontal workload autoscaling with Node autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Other common Pod scheduling constraints include Node affinity, inter-Pod affinity, or a requirement for a particular storage volume.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The specifics of the provisioned Nodes (for example the amount of resources, the presence of a given label) depend on autoscaler configuration.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscalers can either choose them from a pre-defined set of Node configurations, or use auto-provisioning.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Node auto-provisioning is a mode of provisioning in which a user doesn't have to fully configure the specifics of the Nodes that can be provisioned.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Instead, the autoscaler dynamically chooses the Node configuration based on the pending Pods it's reacting to, as well as pre-configured constraints (for example, the minimum amount of resources or the need for a given label).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The main consideration when running a cluster is ensuring that all schedulable pods are running, whilst keeping the cost of the cluster as low as possible.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] To achieve this, the Pods' resource requests should utilize as much of the Nodes' resources as possible.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] From this perspective, the overall Node utilization in a cluster can be used as a proxy for how cost-effective the cluster is.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Correctly setting the resource requests of your Pods is as important to the overall cost-effectiveness of a cluster as optimizing Node utilization.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Nodes in your cluster can be automatically *consolidated* in order to improve the overall Node utilization, and in turn the cost-effectiveness of the cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Consolidation happens through removing a set of underutilized Nodes from the cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Optionally, a different set of Nodes can be provisioned to replace them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Consolidation, like provisioning, only considers Pod resource requests and not real resource usage when making decisions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] For the purpose of consolidation, a Node is considered *empty* if it only has DaemonSet and static Pods running on it.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Removing empty Nodes during consolidation is more straightforward than non-empty ones, and autoscalers often have optimizations designed specifically for consolidating empty Nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Removing non-empty Nodes during consolidation is disruptive—the Pods running on them are terminated, and possibly have to be recreated (for example by a Deployment).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] However, all such recreated Pods should be able to schedule on existing Nodes in the cluster, or the replacement Nodes provisioned as part of consolidation.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscalers predict how a recreated Pod will likely be scheduled after a Node is provisioned or consolidated, but they don't control the actual scheduling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Because of this, some Pods might become pending as a result of consolidation - if for example a completely new Pod appears while consolidation is being performed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscaler configuration may also enable triggering consolidation by other conditions (for example, the time elapsed since a Node was created), in order to optimize different properties (for example, the maximum lifespan of Nodes in a cluster).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The details of how consolidation is performed depend on the configuration of a given autoscaler.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The functionalities described in previous sections are provided by Node *autoscalers*.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] In addition to the Kubernetes API, autoscalers also need to interact with cloud provider APIs to provision and consolidate Nodes.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] This means that they need to be explicitly integrated with each supported cloud provider.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The performance and feature set of a given autoscaler can differ between cloud provider integrations.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Cluster Autoscaler and Karpenter are the two Node autoscalers currently sponsored by SIG Autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] From the perspective of a cluster user, both autoscalers should provide a similar Node autoscaling experience.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Both will provision new Nodes for unschedulable Pods, and both will consolidate the Nodes that are no longer optimally utilized.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Different autoscalers may also provide features outside the Node autoscaling scope described on this page, and those additional features may differ between them.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Consult the sections below, and the linked documentation for the individual autoscalers to decide which autoscaler fits your use case better.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Cluster Autoscaler adds or removes Nodes to pre-configured *Node groups*.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Node groups generally map to some sort of cloud provider resource group (most commonly a Virtual Machine group).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] A single instance of Cluster Autoscaler can simultaneously manage multiple Node groups.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] When provisioning, Cluster Autoscaler will add Nodes to the group that best fits the requests of pending Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] When consolidating, Cluster Autoscaler always selects specific Nodes to remove, as opposed to just resizing the underlying cloud provider resource group.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Karpenter auto-provisions Nodes based on NodePool configurations provided by the cluster operator.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Karpenter handles all aspects of node lifecycle, not just autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] This includes automatically refreshing Nodes once they reach a certain lifetime, and auto-upgrading Nodes when new worker Node images are released.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] It works directly with individual cloud provider resources (most commonly individual Virtual Machines), and doesn't rely on cloud provider resource groups.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Node autoscaling usually works in response to Pods—it provisions new Nodes to accommodate unschedulable Pods, and then consolidates the Nodes once they're no longer needed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Horizontal workload autoscaling automatically scales the number of workload replicas to maintain a desired average resource utilization across the replicas.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] In other words, it automatically creates new Pods in response to application load, and then removes the Pods once the load decreases.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] You can use Node autoscaling together with horizontal workload autoscaling to autoscale the Nodes in your cluster based on the average real resource utilization of your Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] If the application load increases, the average utilization of its Pods should also increase, prompting workload autoscaling to create new Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Node autoscaling should then provision new Nodes to accommodate the new Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Once the application load decreases, workload autoscaling should remove unnecessary Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Node autoscaling should, in turn, consolidate the Nodes that are no longer needed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] If configured correctly, this pattern ensures that your application always has the Node capacity to handle load spikes if needed, but you don't have to pay for the capacity when it's not needed.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] When using Node autoscaling, it's important to set Pod resource requests correctly.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] If the requests of a given Pod are too low, provisioning a new Node for it might not help the Pod actually run.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] If the requests of a given Pod are too high, it might incorrectly prevent consolidating its Node.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Vertical workload autoscaling automatically adjusts the resource requests of your Pods based on their historical resource usage.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] You can use Node autoscaling together with vertical workload autoscaling in order to adjust the resource requests of your Pods while preserving Node autoscaling capabilities in your cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] When using Node autoscaling, it's not recommended to set up vertical workload autoscaling for DaemonSet Pods.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Autoscalers have to predict what DaemonSet Pods on a new Node will look like in order to predict available Node resources.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Vertical workload autoscaling might make these predictions unreliable, leading to incorrect scaling decisions.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] This section describes components providing functionality related to Node autoscaling.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] The descheduler is a component providing Node consolidation functionality based on custom policies, as well as other features related to optimizing Nodes and Pods (for example deleting frequently restarting Pods).
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] Cluster Proportional Autoscaler and Cluster Proportional Vertical Autoscaler provide horizontal, and vertical workload autoscaling based on the number of Nodes in the cluster.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/node-autoscaling] You can read more in autoscaling based on cluster size.
[src:cluster-autoscaling/provisioning-technology] In telecommunications, **provisioning** involves the process of preparing and equipping a network to allow it to provide new services to its users.
